'''Joel Anthony Selwood''' (born 26 May 1988) is an [[Australian rules football]]er and the current captain of the [[Geelong Football Club]] in the [[Australian Football League]] (AFL). A midfielder, {{convert|1.82|m|ft|sigfig=2}} tall and weighing {{convert|86|kg|sigfig=2}}, Selwood is able to contribute [[Australian rules football positions#Midfield|inside or outside]] while [[Midfielder (Australian Rules)|on the ball]].

A standout junior [[Track and field athletics|track and field athlete]] and footballer, Selwood entered top-level football early, joining the [[TAC Cup]] competition as a [[TAC Cup#Age eligibility|bottom-aged player]]. His accomplishments as a junior included [[Most Valuable Player]] awards at state and international levels, captaining Australia in the [[International Rules Series]], and selection in the [[All-Australian]] and [[TAC Cup|TAC Cup Team of the Year]] sides. Despite a serious knee injury during his final year of junior football, Selwood was selected with Geelong's first [[AFL Draft|pick]], and seventh overall, in the [[2006 AFL Draft]].

Selwood made his AFL debut in 2007, winning the [[AFL Rising Star Award]] and [[AFLPA Awards|AFLPA Best First Year Player Award]]. He has since become a [[AFL premiership medallion|triple premiership player]], a two-time [[All-Australian]], a [[Carji Greeves Medal]]list, and the youngest-ever recipient of the [[AFLPA Awards|AFLPA Robert Rose Most Courageous Player Award]]. Selwood has also represented the [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victorian]] state team as the youngest player to feature in the [[all-star]] event, and was awarded the [[Michael Tuck Medal]] following Geelong's 2009 [[NAB Cup]] victory. As of 2011, Selwood holds the second highest winning–percentage record of any player in AFL history, helping the club reach three successive [[AFL Grand Final]]s from 2007–2009 and another in 2011.

Selwood's on-field success has led to several commercial and ambassadorial deals with companies including: [[Asics]], [[Auskick]], [[Cotton On]], [[National Australia Bank]], [[Seeing Eye Dogs Australia]], and [[The Smith's Snackfood Company|Smith's]].

==Early life==
Joel Selwood was born to Bryce and Maree Selwood in the country town of [[Bendigo, Victoria]].&lt;ref name=&quot;hard&quot;&gt;Gleeson, M, [http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/news/hard-selwood/2007/08/31/1188067368443.html &quot;Hard Selwood&quot;], ''The Age'', 1 September 2007, accessed 19 September 2007&lt;/ref&gt; He was raised in a family of sportspeople. His mother Maree was a top runner and tennis player, and elder twins Adam and Troy were identified as talented footballers at a young age.&lt;ref&gt;McClure, G, [http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2005/07/14/1120934358428.html?from=storyrhs &quot;Selwoods take it one son at a time&quot;], ''The Age'', 5 July 2005, accessed 4 October 2007&lt;/ref&gt; As a two-year-old, Selwood was forced to wear [[Shin splints|splints]] on his leg to help overcome a walking disability.&lt;ref name=&quot;hard&quot; /&gt;

Selwood displayed athletic talent from an early age.&lt;ref name=&quot;hard&quot; /&gt; He was the state [[hurdling]] champion from under-10s through to the under-15s, and in one year held every running and jumping record at the Bendigo Sports Centre, except the [[100 metres|100&amp;nbsp;metres sprint]].&lt;ref name=&quot;hard&quot; /&gt; Growing up with his older brothers, Selwood was accustomed to playing with bigger teammates and opponents. By the time he was eight years old, he had played his first competitive game of football, against children four years his senior, and had kicked three [[Laws of Australian football#Scoring|goals]].&lt;ref name=&quot;hard&quot; /&gt;

Selwood played junior football with the [[Sandhurst Football Club]], until he was chosen to play for the [[Bendigo Pioneers]] in the [[TAC Cup]] competition throughout 2006.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2005/07/14/1120934358428.html?from=storyrhs &quot;Selwoods take it one son at a time&quot;], ''The Age'', 5 July 2005, accessed 4 October 2007&lt;/ref&gt; Although his age made him ineligible to enter the [[2005 AFL Draft]], Selwood's accomplishments during the year led to AFL Talent Manager Kevin Sheehan rating him &quot;the best 17-year-old in Australia&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;best&quot;&gt;[http://bendigo.yourguide.com.au/news/sport/general/selwood-in-running-for-top-award/1020068.html &quot;Selwood in running for top award&quot;], ''The Bendigo Advertiser'', 12 July 2007, accessed 5 December 2007&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood received an array of accolades and honours as a [[TAC Cup#Age eligibility|bottom-aged player]],&lt;ref name=&quot;best&quot; /&gt; winning mid-year State honours for Victoria Country in the AFL National Championships. His performances in the championships earned him end-of-year [[All-Australian]] honours and the [[Most Valuable Player]] award for Victoria Country. In addition, he was named in the TAC Cup Team of the Year, awarded a scholarship within the prestigious [[Australian Institute of Sport|AIS-AFL Academy]], and subsequently captained his older teammates in the annual under-18s [[International Rules Series]] in Ireland. His performances in Ireland earned him the [[Ron Barassi|Ron Barassi Medal]], as the adjudicated Most Valuable Player of the tour.&lt;ref name=&quot;star&quot;&gt;Witham, J, [http://afl.com.au/Season2007/News/NewsArticle/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsId=42318 &quot;Joel Selwood wins NAB AFL Rising Star nomination&quot;], Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, 1 May 2007, accessed 19 September 2007&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood's achievements in local football were recognised when he was listed as a finalist in the 2006 Bendigo Sports Star of the Year Award.&lt;ref name = &quot;bendigo&quot;&gt;The Bendigo Advertiser, [http://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/news/local/news/general/selwood-creates-history/1775205.aspx?storypage=1 &quot;Selwood creates history&quot;], ''The Bendigo Advertiser'', 13 March 2010, accessed15 March 2010&lt;/ref&gt;

Returning in 2006 with the Pioneers, Selwood entered his final year of junior football as one of the top rated prospects in his age group.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.nab.com.au/About_Us/0,,89476,00.html &quot;Joel Selwood wins the NAB AFL Rising Star Award&quot;], National Australia Bank, 5 September 2007, accessed 16 December 2007&lt;/ref&gt; His achievements at the junior level were recognised early by the [[AFLPA|AFL Player's Association]], when he was awarded the [[AFLPA Awards|Mike Fitzpatrick Scholarship]],&lt;ref&gt;Murnane, J, [http://www.aflpa.com.au/index.cfm?id=27EB61B6-D819-4F95-8DFC8DB806C87341 &quot;Nine AFLPA Mike Fitzpatrick scholarship selected in AFL draft&quot;], Australian Football League Players Association, 27 November 2006, accessed 19 May 2008&lt;/ref&gt; and the AFL Life Members Education Fund Award.&lt;ref&gt;[http://collingwoodfc.com.au/Season2007/News/NewsArticle/tabid/5586/Default.aspx?newsId=51147 &quot;Naitanui already making headlines&quot;], Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, 14 September 2007, accessed 19 May 2008&lt;/ref&gt; Rewarded with the captaincy of Bendigo for his final season, Selwood again won mid-year State honours for Victoria Country. However, a knee injury occurred only six rounds into the competition forcing him to undergo surgery—his fourth knee operation within two years—prematurely ending his season.&lt;ref name=&quot;missionP140&quot;&gt;Gullan, p. 140.&lt;/ref&gt;

==AFL career==
===2007: Debut===

Selwood was drafted by the [[Geelong Football Club]] with their first selection, and was the seventh overall draft pick in the [[2006 AFL Draft]].&lt;ref&gt;Walls, R, [http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/news/the-next-generation-of-superstars/2007/06/22/1182019372315.html &quot;The next generation of superstars&quot;], ''The Age'', 23 June 2007, accessed 3 October 2007&lt;/ref&gt; Although many recruiting scouts viewed him as &quot;the finest pure footballer in the draft&quot;,&lt;ref name=&quot;mum&quot;&gt;Gleeson, M, [http://www.theage.com.au/handheld/realfooty/articles/2006/11/25/1164341455071.html &quot;Geelong captures a Selwood and calms a mother's heart&quot;], ''The Age'', 26 November 2007, accessed 19 September 2007&lt;/ref&gt; and a potential top pick, there was still concern surrounding the durability of his knee.&lt;ref name=&quot;mum&quot; /&gt; Nonetheless, as the equal highest-ever draft pick for the Cats,&lt;ref name=&quot;ggP18&quot;&gt;Slattery, p. 18.&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood made his debut in the opening round of the [[2007 AFL Season|2007 AFL premiership season]] and missed only four games during the regular season.&lt;ref name=&quot;statsgames&quot;&gt;[http://www.footywire.com/afl/footy/pg-geelong-cats--joel-selwood?year=2007 &quot;Joel Selwood 2007 game statistics&quot;], footywire.com, accessed 21 July 2009&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Image:Joel Selwood in 2007.jpg|thumb|left|Selwood leaves the ground after a game in 2007. |alt=Wearing a navy sleeveless jersey and shorts, young male athlete strides from the grass surface of the playing arena.]]
Selwood's transition to the AFL drew positive comments throughout the footballing community;&lt;ref name=&quot;ggP81&quot;&gt;Slattery, p. 81.&lt;/ref&gt; former [[Brisbane Lions|Brisbane]] coach [[Leigh Matthews]] noted how &quot;from [his] first game ... he looked like he had played 200 of them&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;Morton, J. [http://www.lions.com.au/Default.aspx?tabid=5085&amp;newsId=49047 &quot;Lions' Leuenberger earns rave reviews&quot;], Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, 13 August 2007. accessed 22 May 2008&lt;/ref&gt; Geelong coach [[Mark Thompson (footballer)|Mark Thompson]] labelled the 18-year-old Selwood the best youngster to have come under his tutelage during his time at the club.&lt;ref name=&quot;risingstar&quot;&gt;Gullan, S, [http://www.heraldsun.news.com.au/footy/common/story_page/0,8033,22069616%255E19766,00.html &quot;Rising Star award down to two&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 14 July 2007, accessed 19 September 2007&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Witham, J, [http://www.afl.com.au/Season2007/News/NewsArticle/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsId=50593 &quot;Selwood reminiscent of Bartel&quot;], Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, 5 September 2007, accessed 19 September 2007&lt;/ref&gt; From the beginning, Selwood showed an ability to influence games; in just his fourth appearance he led his older and more experienced teammates with a game of 25&amp;nbsp;disposals and nine tackles. This achievement, described as inspiring,&lt;ref name=&quot;missionP70&quot;&gt;Gullan, p. 70.&lt;/ref&gt; earned him an [[AFL Rising Star Award]] nomination. The Geelong coaching staff had a highlights package made of this performance, to screen to the rest of the team during the match review later that week.&lt;ref name=&quot;missionP79&quot;&gt;Gullan, p. 79.&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood's impact on the game as a first–year player prompted numerous comparisons to [[Chris Judd]], who a few years earlier had been lauded for his first-year success as an 18-year-old.&lt;ref name=&quot;judd&quot;/&gt;

At the conclusion of the home and away period, Selwood's regular contributions resulted in several individual accolades. Polling 44 out of a possible 45&amp;nbsp;votes, he was awarded the inaugural [[Ron Evans|Ron Evans Medal]] as the winner of the AFL Rising Star Award.&lt;ref&gt;Shields, J &quot;[http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2007/09/06/6636_geelong_sports.html &quot;Joel Selwood's star qualities&quot;], ''The Geelong Advertiser'', 6 September 2007, accessed 5 December 2007&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood earned the maximum five votes from eight of the nine judges, the other awarding him four out of five. This meant that eight of the nine judges rated him as the best nominee.&lt;ref name=&quot;risingstaraward&quot;&gt;[http://www.afl.com.au/Season2007/News/NewsArticle/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsId=50566 &quot;Joel Selwood wins the NAB AFL Rising Star award&quot;], Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, 5 September 2007, accessed 19 September 2007&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood was also awarded the prestigious [[AFLPA Awards|AFLPA Best First Year Player Award]], winning  over 70% of all votes from his peers. He became only the fourth player to win both the major awards for first–year players.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.heraldsun.news.com.au/footy/common/story_page/0,8033,22501129%255E19766,00.html &quot;Ablett wins AFLPA MVP award&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 29 September 2007, accessed 29 September 2007&lt;/ref&gt;

{{Quote box
 | quote  = There are very few that play like Joel Selwood plays and have such a dominant year ... to have that type of year, I think that's a bit of a rarity.
 | source = '''[[Kevin Sheehan]]'''&lt;ref name=&quot;unique&quot;/&gt;
 | width  = 35%
 | align  = right
}}

Having helped Geelong finish first on the ladder and win the [[McClelland Trophy]], Selwood made his finals debut in the 2nd Qualifying Final against the [[North Melbourne Football Club|Kangaroos]] (now North Melbourne) at the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]] (MCG).&lt;ref&gt;Boulon, M, [http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/news/cats-rising-star-looks-for-a-flag/2007/09/05/1188783319901.html?s_cid=rss_sport &quot;Cats' rising star looks for a flag&quot;], ''The Age'', 6 September 2007, accessed 5 December 2007&lt;/ref&gt; In front of nearly 80,000&amp;nbsp;spectators, Selwood amassed 22&amp;nbsp;[[disposal]]s, five [[mark (Australian football)|marks]], five clearances, six [[50-metre arc|inside 50s]], five [[tackle (football move)|tackles]], and five score assists, helping Geelong to a club finals record 106&amp;nbsp;point victory.&lt;ref name=&quot;stats&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Lienert, S. [http://www.news.com.au/perthnow/story/0,21598,22388575-5011880,00.html &quot;Cats pound 'Roos in record thrashing&quot;], ''Perth Now'', 9 September 2008, accessed 26 May 2008&lt;/ref&gt; Although Selwood struggled to contribute in the Preliminary Final against Collingwood two weeks later,&lt;ref name=&quot;ycP101&quot;&gt;Townley, p. 101.&lt;/ref&gt; he returned to form for the [[2007 AFL Grand Final]] at the MCG against [[Port Adelaide Football Club|Port Adelaide]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2007/09/29/7353_gfc.html &quot;Big brother Adam expects Joel to handle hype&quot;], ''The Geelong Advertiser'', 29 September 2007, accessed 5 December 2007&lt;/ref&gt; With 18&amp;nbsp;disposals, five marks, five clearances—the most of any Geelong player—seven inside 50s, four tackles, and an equal game-high four score assists,&lt;ref&gt;[http://bendigo.yourguide.com.au/news/sport/general/joels-stunning-season/1061910.html &quot;Joel's stunning season&quot;], ''The Bendigo Advertiser'', 1 October 2007, accessed 9 February 2008&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood helped the Cats to a record 119&amp;nbsp;point win.&lt;ref&gt;[http://afl.com.au/Season2007/News/NewsArticle/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsId=51977 &quot;Premiership a doddle for teenage sensation&quot;], Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, 30 September 2007, accessed 5 December 2007&lt;/ref&gt; At 19&amp;nbsp;years of age, Selwood became the youngest person to play in a winning Grand Final team in 10&amp;nbsp;years.&lt;ref name=&quot;young&quot;&gt;Williams, R, [http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,22510530-23211,00.html &quot;Selwood wanted premiership ride&quot;], Fox Sports, 1 October 2007, accessed 1 October 2007&lt;/ref&gt; He was also the first to win the AFL Rising Star Award and play in a [[AFL Premiership|premiership]] side within the same season,&lt;ref name=&quot;ggP18&quot; /&gt; making him one of the most accomplished first&amp;nbsp;year players in league history.&lt;ref name=&quot;unique&quot;&gt;Sherwood, M, [http://canberra.yourguide.com.au/news/sport/afl/selwoods-season-rare-for-a-rookie-sheehan/1063231.html &quot;Selwood's season rare for a rookie: Sheehan&quot;], ''The Canberra Times'', 3 October 2007, accessed 8 November 2007&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;ggP48&quot;&gt;Slattery, p. 48.&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood's debut year achievements resulted in his becoming AFL's highest-paid first–year player.&lt;ref&gt;Barrett, D. [http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/sport/afl/story/0,,22509283-19742,00.html &quot;Cats cash in on flag&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 1 October 2007, accessed 26 May 2008&lt;/ref&gt;

Selwood finished the season ranked first among all first–year players in several major statistical categories;&lt;ref name=&quot;stats&quot; /&gt; total possessions (405), disposals per game (19.3), kicks (216), handpasses (189), marks (109), tackles (94)—the most ever by any first–year AFL player&lt;ref name=&quot;tackle&quot;&gt;[http://stats.afl.com.au/public/home.shtml &quot;AFL Statistics], Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, accessed 13 May 2008&lt;/ref&gt;—and tackles per game (4.5). His 23&amp;nbsp;score assists during the season also ranked him within the top ten in the league.&lt;ref name=&quot;stats&quot; /&gt; Selwood added to his list of first&amp;nbsp;year honours at season's end with the Geelong Football Club Best First Year Player Award, along with a top 20 placing in the [[Carji Greeves Medal|Club Champion award]].&lt;ref name=&quot;awards&quot;&gt;[http://gfc.com.au/TheClub/Players/PlayerProfile/tabid/8137/playerId/15610/teamId/30/typeId/2/Default.aspx &quot;Profile at Geelong's official website&quot;], Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, accessed 4 November 2007&lt;/ref&gt; He also received several media end&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;year sporting awards.&lt;ref&gt;[http://bendigo.yourguide.com.au/news/sport/general/young-guns-keep-firing/1068904.html &quot;Young guns keep firing&quot;], ''The Bendigo Advertiser'', 13 October 2007, accessed 4 November 2007&lt;/ref&gt;

===2008: &quot;Boy wonder&quot;===
[[Image:Joel Selwood against Richmond.jpg|thumb|right|Selwood prepares to handpass the football during a game.|alt=Young male athlete stands in a navy blue and white striped sleeveless shirt and blue navy shorts. With an opponent approaching him, he looks to the left and prepares to handpass the red football.]]
Selwood continued to establish himself as a key player in the Geelong midfield during the [[2008 AFL season]],&lt;ref name=&quot;youngcat&quot;&gt;Ralph, J, [http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,24322889-19742,00.html &quot;Young cat Joel Selwood impresses his peers at Geelong&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 10 September 2008, accessed 29 September 2008&lt;/ref&gt; helping the Cats achieve a record-equalling 21-win season and secure the McClelland Trophy for the second successive year.&lt;ref&gt;Ralph, J, [http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/sport/afl/story/0,26576,24241844-19742,00.html &quot;Terry Wallace says Cats flag certainty&quot;] ''The Herald Sun'', 26 August 2008, accessed 28 August 2008&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood also claimed the third–longest all-time winning streak by an individual player in VFL/AFL history; 25&amp;nbsp;successive wins before a mid-season loss to Collingwood.&lt;ref name=&quot;streak&quot;&gt;McClure, G, [http://www.theage.com.au/news/sport/so-thats-where-that-fan-got-to/2008/04/29/1209234865339.html &quot;So that's where that fan got to&quot;], ''The Age'', 30 April 2008, accessed 30 April 2008&lt;/ref&gt; His standout season was rewarded when he was selected to play for [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victoria]] in the [[AFL Hall of Fame Tribute Match]] [[all-star game|All-Star event]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://afl.com.au/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsid=59061 &quot;Vics name eight Cats&quot;] Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, 4 May 2008, accessed 4 May 2008&lt;/ref&gt; In gaining selection for the Victorian team, Selwood, at 19&amp;nbsp;years of age, became the youngest player to represent &quot;[[Victoria Australian rules football team|The Big V]]&quot; in more than 12&amp;nbsp;years.&lt;ref&gt;Bews, A, [http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2008/05/07/13647_geelong_sports.html &quot;Game's state of pride&quot;], ''The Geelong Advertiser'', 7 May 2008, accessed 7 May 2008&lt;/ref&gt; He was also selected for the preliminary 2008 [[All-Australian]] squad, placed sixth for the [[Leigh Matthews Trophy]] as the [[Leigh Matthews Trophy|AFLPA Most Valuable Player]], and finished third in voting for the [[AFLPA Awards|Robert Rose Most Courageous Player Award]].&lt;ref&gt;Siragusa, L, [http://afl.com.au/News/NEWSARTICLE/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsId=66551 &quot;Didak nominated for AFLPA MVP despite suspension&quot;] Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, 28 August 2008, accessed 28 August 2008&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood also polled 19&amp;nbsp;votes in the [[Brownlow Medal]], awarded to the &quot;best and fairest&quot; player in the AFL, to place fifth overall, and second among his teammates.&lt;ref name=&quot;youngcat&quot; /&gt; Selwood's consistency and performances over his first two seasons was also recognised by the AFL Coaches Association, who awarded him the Best Young Player Award.&lt;ref&gt;[http://aflca.com.au/index.php?id=14&amp;tx_ttnews[tt_news&amp;#93;=37 &quot;AFL Coaches Association: AFLCA Industry Awards&quot;], AFL Coaches Association, accessed 22 September 2009&lt;/ref&gt; Geelong qualified for the [[2008 AFL Finals Series|finals series]] and progressed to the [[2008 AFL Grand Final|Grand Final]] for the second consecutive year, but were defeated by [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]]. Selwood's performance in the final, during which he gathered 29&amp;nbsp;disposals—including a team-high nine contested possessions—six marks, six tackles, and six inside 50s, were recognised as he placed fourth in [[Norm Smith Medal]] voting for best afield in the Grand Final.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/news/norm-smith-medal-votes/2008/09/27/1222217592483.html &quot;Norm Smith medal votes&quot;], ''The Age'', 28 September 2008, accessed 29 September 2008&lt;/ref&gt;

Selwood's year, during which he averaged more than 25&amp;nbsp;disposals, 4&amp;nbsp;marks, and 4&amp;nbsp;tackles per game, was also rewarded with a top five finish in the [[Carji Greeves Medal]] (Geelong's Best and Fairest).&lt;ref&gt;Williams, R, [http://www.afl.com.au/News/NEWSARTICLE/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsId=65818 &quot;Joel Corey beats Gary Ablett to win Cats' b&amp;f&quot;], Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, 3 October 2008, accessed 4 October 2008&lt;/ref&gt; He finished the season ranked within the top ten in the league for possessions (613), disposals per game (25.5), and handpasses (327).&lt;ref name=&quot;stats&quot; /&gt; His total of 63&amp;nbsp;free kicks earned during the season was also the highest recorded since the AFL began in 1990, breaking the previous record of 54 set by [[Luke Darcy]] five years earlier.&lt;ref name=&quot;frees&quot;&gt;Broad, B, [http://www.afl.com.au/News/NEWSARTICLE/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsId=65818 &quot;Young cat keeping clean record&quot;], Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, 19 August 2008, accessed 4 October 2008&lt;/ref&gt;

With his rookie contract due to expire, concern mounted during the year over Geelong's ability to retain Selwood beyond the season.&lt;ref name=&quot;contract&quot;&gt;Sheridan, N, [http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/news/cats-selwood-still-to-resign/2008/04/24/1208743155618.html &quot;Cats' Selwood still to re-sign&quot;], ''The Age'', 25 April 2008, accessed 8 May 2008&lt;/ref&gt; With almost half of their premiership–winning team out of contract, Geelong could only offer contracts paying significantly less than other clubs.&lt;ref name=&quot;contract&quot; /&gt; However, Selwood signed a new two–year deal with the club, citing &quot;club success and future opportunities&quot; as his reasons for accepting the reduced salary.&lt;ref&gt;Sheridan, N, [http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/news/selwood-inks-deal-with-geelong/2008/05/07/1210131067940.html &quot;Selwood inks deal with Geelong&quot;], ''The Age'', 8 May 2008, accessed 8 May 2008&lt;/ref&gt;

===2009: Premiership pedigree===
[[Image:Joel Selwood in 2009.jpg|thumb|left|Selwood prepares to kick the football during a 2009 finals game.|alt=Young male athlete stands in a white and navy blue and striped sleeveless shirt and white shorts. He stands alone and looks to the right while preparing the kick the football.]]
Before the 2009 AFL season, Selwood was appointed to the club's seven-man leadership group at just 20&amp;nbsp;years of age.&lt;ref&gt;Gullan, S, [http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,24909946-5016158,00.html &quot;Gary Ablett, Joel Selwood and Jimmy Bartel step up&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 19 January 2009, accessed 12 February 2009&lt;/ref&gt; After the 2008 Grand Final loss ended Geelong's previous season, Selwood and his teammates began their 2009 campaign by capturing the pre-season [[NAB Cup]] for the second time in four years.&lt;ref name = &quot;nabcup&quot;&gt;Cullen, M, [http://www.afl.com.au/news/newsarticle/tabid/208/newsid/73077/default.aspx &quot;Cats belt Pies in NAB Cup GF&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 14 March 2009, accessed 14 March 2009&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood's 33&amp;nbsp;disposals, 11&amp;nbsp;clearances, and 2&amp;nbsp;goals earned him the [[Michael Tuck Medal]] as the player adjudged best afield in this [[2009 NAB Cup|final]].&lt;ref name = &quot;nabcup&quot;/&gt; In round five, Selwood made his 50th senior appearance, setting a new VFL/AFL record for the highest percentage of wins inside 50&amp;nbsp;games. His involvement in 46&amp;nbsp;victories set a winning percentage of 92 percent.&lt;ref name = &quot;fifty&quot;&gt;[http://stats.rleague.com/afl/stats/alltime/misc_players.html &quot;Joel Selwood Record&quot;], AFL Tables, accessed 27 April 2009&lt;/ref&gt; In addition, Selwood's 50th appearance coincided with the club's own record-setting effort for the most successful 50&amp;nbsp;game stretch in VFL/AFL history. Geelong had won 47 out of 50&amp;nbsp;games—Selwood had been involved in 46—eclipsing [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon's]] return of 46&amp;nbsp;wins and 4&amp;nbsp;losses during their dominant stretch during the 1999–2001 seasons.&lt;ref&gt;Sheahan, M, [http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/sport/afl/story/0,26576,25396266-19742,00.html &quot;Greatest Geelong team of all&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 28 April 2009, accessed 4 May 2009&lt;/ref&gt;

During the round seventeen Grand Final rematch against Hawthorn, Selwood achieved career highs of 42&amp;nbsp;disposals, 10&amp;nbsp;marks, and 11&amp;nbsp;tackles.&lt;ref name=&quot;stats&quot;&gt;[http://www.footywire.com/afl/footy/pp-geelong-cats--joel-selwood &quot;Joel Selwood statistics&quot;], footywire.com, accessed 4 August 2009&lt;/ref&gt; Geelong midfielder [[Cameron Ling]] described Selwood's performance as: &quot;Absolutely amazing... He just single-handedly lifted the whole group with his intensity around the ball. It's surprising that he's only in his third year. He's something pretty special&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;Zander, J, [http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/07/25/2636317.htm?site=local &quot;Cats claw over top of Hawks&quot;], ''ABC'', 25 July 2009, accessed 5 August 2009&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood helped Geelong compile an 18–4 win-loss record during the season to become the first team in league history to produce three consecutive home and away campaigns with 18 or more wins.&lt;ref&gt;Pace, R, [http://www.geelongcats.com.au/geelongnews/newsarticle/tabid/3933/newsid/83622/default.aspx &quot;Cats on Song&quot;], Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, 27 August 2009, accessed 7 September 2009&lt;/ref&gt; Geelong qualified for the [[2009 AFL Finals Series|finals series]] in second position on the ladder, before reaching the preliminary final for the third consecutive season. Selwood matched a career–high in finals games with 29&amp;nbsp;disposals and 9&amp;nbsp;marks during the Cats 73&amp;nbsp;point win over Collingwood, leading the club to their third successive Grand Final appearance.&lt;ref&gt;Rucci, M, [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/cats-blitz-pies-by-73-points/story-e6frf9jf-1225777029871 &quot;Cats blitz Pies by 73 points&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 19 September 2009, accessed 19 September 2009&lt;/ref&gt; During the final against [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]], Selwood addressed the playing group with a &quot;stirring speech&quot;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/news/local/news/general/grand-day-for-bendigos-joel/1634329.aspx?storypage=0 &quot;Grand day for Bendigo's Joel&quot;], ''The Bendigo Advertiser'', 28 September 2009, accessed 1 October 2009&lt;/ref&gt; as Geelong entered the half–time break trailing by 6&amp;nbsp;points. Teammate [[Andrew Mackie]] lauded Selwood as &quot;a born leader&quot;&lt;ref name = &quot;speech&quot;&gt;Silkstone, D, [http://www.realfooty.com.au/news/rfnews/cats-who-got-the-dream/2009/09/27/1253989826496.html?page=2 &quot;Cats who got the dream&quot;], ''The Age'', 28 September 2009, accessed 1 October 2009&lt;/ref&gt; and credited the team's second half turnaround to Selwood's reminder to &quot;go back to basics and focus upon tackling&quot;.&lt;ref name = &quot;speech&quot; /&gt; Selwood finished the game with 24&amp;nbsp;disposals—including a team–high 12&amp;nbsp;contested possessions and equal game–high 16&amp;nbsp;handpasses—4&amp;nbsp;marks, 6&amp;nbsp;clearances, a team–high 10&amp;nbsp;first possessions, 3&amp;nbsp;tackles, and 1&amp;nbsp;goal to help the Cats record a 12&amp;nbsp;point win and secure their second premiership in three seasons.&lt;ref&gt;Davis, G, [http://www.news.com.au/adelaidenow/story/0,22606,26133671-5016212,00.html &quot;Winning words: 'Don't panic' says Geelong coach Mark Thompson&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 27 September 2009, accessed 28 September 2009&lt;/ref&gt;

Selwood's standout year was recognised by his peers when he became the youngest-ever winner of the AFLPA Robert Rose Most Courageous Player Award, and placed fifth for the Leigh Matthews Trophy as the AFLPA Most Valuable Player.&lt;ref&gt;Tullberg, J, [http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,26041094-19742,00.html &quot;Gary Ablett wins third Most Valuable Player of the Year for the AFLPA Awards&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 7 September 2009, accessed 7 September 2009&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Stokes, B, [http://aflpa.com.au/node/760 &quot;AFLPA announced nominations for the 2009 MVP Awards&quot;], Australian Football League Players Association, 4 September 2009, accessed 7 September 2009&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood also finished sixth in the [[2009 Brownlow Medal|Brownlow Medal]], polling 16&amp;nbsp;votes to finish second at Geelong behind eventual winner [[Gary Ablett, Jr.|Gary Ablett]].&lt;ref&gt;3AW Football, [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/afl-brownlow-medal-count-club-by-club/story-fn422eni-1225777929153 &quot;2009 AFL Brownlow medal count club-by-club&quot;], 22 September 2009, accessed 22 September 2009&lt;/ref&gt; He became the first footballer to win the Bendigo Sports Star of the Year Award, adding to his season's list of accolades.&lt;ref name = &quot;bendigo&quot;/&gt; After averaging 28&amp;nbsp;disposals and 5&amp;nbsp;tackles per game over the course of the season, Selwood was also awarded with [[All-Australian]] honours for the first time in his career and a second successive top five placing for the Carji Greeves Medal.&lt;ref&gt;Auciello, M, [http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2009/09/15/104041_gfc.html &quot;Five Geelong Cats selected in All-Australian team&quot;], ''The Geelong Advertiser'', 15 September 2009, accessed 15 September 2009&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Cullen, M, [http://www.gfc.com.au/geelongnews/newsarticle/tabid/3933/newsid/85606/default.aspx &quot;Ablett, Enright tie for B&amp;F&quot;], Geelong Football Club &amp; Bigpond Network, 1 October 2009, accessed 1 October 2009&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood finished the year ranked fourth in the league for total disposals (691), third for total handpasses (389), second for contested possessions (236) and eighth for hard-ball gets.&lt;ref&gt;3AW Football, [http://www.3aw.com.au/blogs/3aw-football-blog/all-australian-team-2009-official/20090914-fnw2.html &quot;All Australian 2009 Official&quot;], 14 September 2009, accessed 15 September 2009&lt;/ref&gt; For the second successive season, he also led the league for total free kicks earned (59) and finished the year ranked within the top five at Geelong in several major statistical categories.&lt;ref name=&quot;stats&quot;/&gt;

===2010: Carji Greeves Medallist===
Prior to the 2010 AFL season, Selwood was retained as the youngest member of the club's revamped leadership group. Despite being unable to defend their NAB Cup title over the pre-season, Geelong re-signed Selwood to a new two-year contract with the club.&lt;ref&gt;Green, B, [http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2010/05/14/173261_gfc.html &quot;Geelong Cats turn focus on holding Gary Ablett after Joel Selwood re-signs &quot;], ''The Geelong Advertiser'', 14 May 2010, accessed 7 June 2010&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood highlighted his desire to &quot;give a little bit back (to Geelong) by working hard and working through the next era of Geelong football&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;Gullan, S, [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/joel-selwood-turns-back-on-gold-coast-says-he-owes-cats/story-e6frf9jf-1225869375881 &quot;Joel Selwood turns back on Gold Coast, says he owes Cats&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 21 May 2010, accessed 16 June 2010&lt;/ref&gt; During the home and away campaign, Selwood set various personal milestones: in a round six fixture against Richmond, Selwood made a career–high 29&amp;nbsp;handpasses—also the third–highest recorded in AFL history&lt;ref&gt;[http://stats.rleague.com/afl/stats/playershi.html &quot;AFL Most Handballs In A Game statistics&quot;], AFL Tables, accessed 10 October 2010&lt;/ref&gt;—while in a round nineteen match against Collingwood he gathered a career–high 20&amp;nbsp;contested possessions.&lt;ref name = &quot;prostats&quot;/&gt; In total, Selwood made 24&amp;nbsp;appearances during the season to help the club achieve a 17–5 record and qualify for the finals series in second position on the ladder. Geelong faced a 2009 Grand Final rematch against St Kilda during the first week of the finals series, and were defeated in a qualifying final for the first time in four years. Selwood was restricted to just four disposals in the first half of the qualifying final loss, his lowest return in a half of football since his debut match in 2007.&lt;ref&gt;Auciello, M, [http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2010/09/09/208561_gfc.html &quot;Geelong star Jimmy Bartel backs teammate Joel Selwood to respond to criticism against Fremantle&quot;], ''The Geelong Advertiser'', 9 September 2010, accessed 10 October 2010&lt;/ref&gt; The following week, he responded with a 33&amp;nbsp;disposal semi–final performance—including a game–high 12&amp;nbsp;contested possessions and career–high 11&amp;nbsp;clearances—to help Geelong defeat Fremantle and progress to the preliminary final for the fourth consecutive season. However, Geelong's defeat to Collingwood subsequently denied them a fourth successive appearance in the Grand Final, and marked Selwood's absence from a Grand Final for the first time in his career to date.

Despite the club's lack of any silverware for the first time in four years, Selwood's individual season was recognised and rewarded on various fronts. He was once again nominated by his peers for both the AFLPA Most Valuable Player Award and the AFLPA Robert Rose Most Courageous Player Award, placing fifth and second overall respectively.&lt;ref&gt;Williams, R, [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/dane-swan-pockets-mvp-awad/story-e6frf9jf-1225915020976 &quot;Dane Swan pockets MVP award&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 6 September 2010, accessed 10 October 2010&lt;/ref&gt; During the [[2010 Brownlow Medal]] count, Selwood polled 21&amp;nbsp;votes to place fourth overall and second at Geelong behind [[Gary Ablett, Jr.]] (26&amp;nbsp;votes).&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/brownlow-votes-club-by-club-20100921-15k5n.html &quot;Brownlow Votes Club by Club&quot;], ''The Age'', 21 September 2010, accessed 10 October 2010&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood was selected in the [[All-Australian]] team for the second successive year, and also placed third in the AFL Coaches Association Champion Player of the Year Award.&lt;ref&gt;Thompson, T, [http://www.worldfootynews.com/article.php/20100921210742691 &quot;2010 Channel 7 AFL Coaches Association Awards&quot;], World Football News, 21 September 2010, accessed 10 October 2010&lt;/ref&gt; He also won his first [[Carji Greeves Medal]], awarded for being the Geelong Football Club's [[best and fairest]] player during the 2010 season.&lt;ref&gt;Gullan, S, [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/joel-selwood-pips-gary-ablett-to-win-his-first-cargi-greeves-medal-for-geelongs-best-and-fairest-player/story-e6frf9jf-1225932576893 &quot;Joel Selwood pips Gary Ablett to win his first Carji Greeves Medal for Geelong's best-and-fairest player&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 1 October 2010, accessed 11 October 2010&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood finished the season ranked eighth in the league for total disposals (677), third for total handpasses (388)—also the 10th most in AFL history—second for total free kicks earned (53), and seventh for total inside 50s (110)&lt;ref name=&quot;stats&quot;/&gt; Selwood highlighted his consistency by gathering over 20 disposals in 21 of 24 games—11 of which were games with 30 or more disposals—and compiling a six game streak during which he gathered over 30 possessions from Round 13 to Round 18.&lt;ref name = &quot;stats&quot;/&gt;

==Player profile==
{{Quote box
 | quote  = He's the type of player I look at from afar and say, 'I'd love to be in the trenches with him'. I love how hard he is at the footy, how humble he is ... He can play inside or outside and can use the footy ... He's going to go down as one of the greats of the last 10 years. With (James) Hird, (Mark) Ricciuto, (Nathan) Buckley and those sort of guys ... (He's in the) same mould as (Michael) Voss
 | source = '''[[Brett Kirk]]'''&lt;ref name=&quot;kirk&quot;&gt;Sheahan, M, [http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/sport/afl/story/0,26576,25311798-19742,00.html &quot;Joel Selwood and Brett Kirk enjoy mutual admiration&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 9 April 2009, accessed 21 April 2009&lt;/ref&gt;
 | width  = 35%
 | align  = right
}}

Selwood is primarily regarded as an [[Australian rules football positions#Midfield|inside midfielder]], and is noted for his physical approach, his ability to find space on the ground, and for winning the ball.&lt;ref name=&quot;ycP19&quot;&gt;Townley, p. 19.&lt;/ref&gt; Leigh Matthews has complimented Selwood as &quot;already the best wet-weather player in the game&quot;,&lt;ref name=&quot;risingstar&quot; /&gt; a view shared by [[Nathan Buckley]], who notes that Selwood &quot;plays with a physicality and intensity that is the benchmark of the competition, consistently (finding) third and fourth efforts to win the contested ball&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;bucks&quot;&gt;Buckley, N, [http://www.theage.com.au/news/rfnews/buckleys-top-10-midfielders/2009/08/14/1249756444568.html &quot;Buckley's top 10 midfielders&quot;], ''The Age'', 15 August 2009, accessed 22 August 2009&lt;/ref&gt; Two-time [[AFLPA Awards|Most Courageous Player Award]] winner [[Jonathan Brown (Australian rules footballer)|Jonathan Brown]] has also praised Selwood for his physical and courageous approach to winning the football, describing him as &quot;one of the blokes (all players) within the AFL love watching&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;youngcat&quot;/&gt; Selwood's teammates [[Joel Corey]] and [[Cameron Ling]] have also acknowledged his maturity. They regard him as one of the most physical players in the game.&lt;ref name=&quot;wonder&quot;&gt;Hanlon, P, [http://www.realfooty.com.au/articles/2008/03/08/1204780133774.html &quot;What next, boy wonder?&quot;], ''The Age'', 9 March 2008, accessed 17 March 2008&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;first&quot;&gt;Shields, J, [http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2007/09/03/6545_news_pf.html &quot;First-year player has made a big impact&quot;], ''The Geelong Advertiser'', 3 September 2007, accessed 17 March 2008&lt;/ref&gt;

Selwood has stated his career intention to &quot;work really hard on the basics&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;game&quot;&gt;Dole, N, [http://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/news/local/sport/football-australian-rules/superb-run/1280492.aspx &quot;Superb run&quot;], ''The Bendigo Advertiser'', 24 September 2008, accessed 4 October 2008&lt;/ref&gt; Despite his admitting to being &quot;not the fastest player, or most skillful&quot;,&lt;ref name=&quot;game&quot; /&gt; his hard running, tackling and [[One percenter (Australian rules football)|one percent plays]] are important elements to his overall game.&lt;ref name=&quot;sheehan&quot;&gt;Sheehan, M, [http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/sport/afl/story/0,26576,25311801-19742,00.html&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 9 April 2009, accessed 21 July 2009&lt;/ref&gt; Because of his aggressive style-of-play, Selwood has gathered a reputation as a &quot;head–over–the–ball specialist&quot;&lt;ref name = &quot;head&quot;&gt;Stevens, M, [http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,26112563-5018851,00.html &quot;Handle Selwood with due care: Geelong star Joel Selwood is the master of earning free kicks&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 23 September 2009, accessed 1 October 2009&lt;/ref&gt; and for consistently putting himself in positions to win free kicks.&lt;ref&gt;Cresswell, J, [http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2009/04/22/64751_gfc.html &quot;Collingwood went to AFL to query Joel Selwood free kicks&quot;], ''The Geelong Advertiser'', 22 April 2009, accessed 22 August 2009&lt;/ref&gt; His ability to &quot;buckle his knees, (get) down and pull his arm up so that the tackler's arm goes up above the neck&quot;&lt;ref&gt;Buckley, N, &quot;Channel 7 broadcast of the Round 21 Geelong vs. Western Bulldogs game during the 2009 AFL season&quot;, 21 August 2009, accessed 2009 August 2009&lt;/ref&gt; is reflected in his regular standing among league leaders for total free kicks received.&lt;ref name = &quot;frees&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name = &quot;head&quot; /&gt; As of 2009, Selwood also holds the AFL record for highest career average for frees received per game (2.28).&lt;ref name = &quot;prostats&quot;&gt;[http://stats.rleague.com/afl/stats/players.html &quot;AFL Tables – Player Records: Season and Game Highs&quot;], AFL Tables, accessed 22 September 2009&lt;/ref&gt; Since his arrival at the club his leadership ability has often been praised, leading to predictions of a future post as club captain.&lt;ref name=&quot;wonder&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;first&quot; /&gt;

During his first three seasons at Geelong, Selwood's all-around ability to contribute as an attacking [[Australian rules football positions#Midfield|inside]] or [[Australian rules football positions#Midfield|outside midfielder]] has been highlighted by his regular ranking among the top five at the club for total disposals, clearances, first possessions, contested possessions, uncontested possessions, tackles, [[50-metre arc|inside 50s]], and score assists.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.gfc.com.au/TheClub/Players/PlayerProfile/tabid/8137/Default.aspx?playerid=15610&amp;typeid=2 &quot;Player Profile – Official AFL website of the Geelong Football Club&quot;], Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, accessed 9 November 2008&lt;/ref&gt; As of 2009, Selwood holds the highest career average for disposals per game among currently active players (24.4) and the second-highest career average for handpasses per game (12.9).&lt;ref name = &quot;prostats&quot;/&gt; Buckley has complimented Selwood's all-around game, making note of his &quot;(preparedness) to pressure the opposition in defence as ferociously as he attacks&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;bucks&quot;/&gt; Throughout his career, Selwood has carried an above–average disposal efficiency of 75%.&lt;ref&gt;[http://superstats.heraldsun.com.au/profile/250321.html &quot;Herald Sun superstats&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', accessed 17 March 2008&lt;/ref&gt; Footballing experts have praised his decision-making ability when considering his overall productivity with the football.&lt;ref name=&quot;risingstar&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;unique&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Burgan, M, [http://www.afl.com.au/Season2007/News/NewsArticle/tabid/7009/Default.aspx?newsId=50538 &quot;Our Rising Star Predictions&quot;], Australian Football League &amp; Bigpond, 5 September 2007, accessed 12 February 2009&lt;/ref&gt;

==Personal life==
Selwood is the third of four children born to Bryce and Maree Selwood. He has three brothers, all having been listed with [[Australian Football League|AFL]] clubs; two older brothers, twins [[Adam Selwood|Adam]] (playing with [[West Coast Eagles|West Coast]]) and [[Troy Selwood|Troy]] (Formerly of the Brisbane Lions and currently the Geelong VFL captain) and a younger brother, [[Scott Selwood|Scott]] (West Coast). Maree was awarded the 2005 [[AFL Players Association]] Mother of the Year Award for her contribution to football through each of her sons.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.aflpa.com.au/index.cfm?id=AF3369C1-04EB-094C-808FA128713DD777 &quot;AFLPA mother of the year award&quot;], Australian Football League Players Association, 6 May 2007, accessed 8 November 2007&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood is also a descendant of the three Crapper brothers, granduncles to Maree, each of whom played VFL football in the 1930s.&lt;ref&gt;[http://bendigo.yourguide.com.au/articles/1093945.html?src=search &quot;Selwood's follow family tradition&quot;], ''The Bendigo Advertiser'', 28 November 2007, accessed 2 February 2008&lt;/ref&gt;

Since winning the [[National Australia Bank]]-sponsored AFL Rising Star Award, Selwood has been involved in several promotions for the bank, in an ambassadorial role and in several television advertisement appearances.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.nab.com.au/Personal_Finance/0,,94807,00.html?campaignID=RUC&amp;WT.mc_id=RUC &quot;NAB – Win $20,000 for a NAB personal loan advertisement&quot;], National Australia Bank, accessed 5 August 2008&lt;/ref&gt; He is also an ambassador for the AFL's junior development program, [[Auskick]], annually acting as a mentor for the junior player deemed 'Auskicker of the Year'.&lt;ref&gt;Ralph, J, [http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/sport/afl/story/0,26576,25102461-19742,00.html &quot;Geelong's Joel Selwood vows Cats' best yet to come&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 25 February 2009, accessed 25 February 2009&lt;/ref&gt; Along with his parents and brothers, Selwood works on behalf of the [[Seeing Eye Dogs Australia|Seeing Eye Dogs Association]] (SEDA) organisation. Selwood and his family sponsor pups who are being trained as a seeing eye dogs—one named &quot;Selwood&quot; in his family's honour. SEDA has said that the family's widespread dispersal around Australia, with Adam and Scott in Western Australia,  Joel and Troy remaining in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], has helped to publicise the organisation's nationwide activity.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.theage.com.au/news/Sport/Brotherly-love-put-aside-at-Geelong/2007/06/16/1181414598688.html &quot;Brotherly love put aside at Geelong&quot;], ''The Age'', 16 June 2007, accessed 19 September 2007&lt;/ref&gt; During the 2010 season, Selwood was officially appointed as the club's community ambassador for various charitable community activities.&lt;ref&gt;Gullan, S, [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/joe-selwoodls-deal-off-the-rack/story-e6frf9jf-1225881091164 &quot;Joel Selwood's deal off the rack&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 18 June 2010, accessed 24 July 2010&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood subsequently became the public face of both the Cotton On Foundation and its sponsorship for the rebuilding of the children's ward at Geelong Hospital.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.gfc.com.au/tabid/3933/default.aspx?newsid=96518 &quot;Selwood runs Geelong&quot;], ''Geelong Football Club &amp; Bigpond'', 17 June 2010, accessed 24 July 2010&lt;/ref&gt;

Early success on the field has led to several endorsement and promotional deals with companies including [[Asics]] and [[The Smith's Snackfood Company|Smith's]].&lt;ref&gt;Ralph, J, [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/joel-content-to-delay-deal/story-e6frf9ix-1225836743686 &quot;Joel content to delay deal&quot;], ''The Herald Sun'', 4 March 2010, accessed 4 March 2010&lt;/ref&gt; These have seen Selwood participate in promotional appearances with rugby league player [[Greg Inglis]] and several television advertisements with [[AFL Hall of Fame]]r [[Peter Daicos]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.asics.com.au/tech40_08.asp &quot;Asics – Our partnerships&quot;], Asics &amp; Microsites, accessed 9 November 2008&lt;/ref&gt; Selwood also features in a special edition Monopoly AFL premiership gameboard, occupying Bow Street.&lt;ref&gt;Breen, D [http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2008/03/14/12181_news.html &quot;Cats strut monopoly boardwalk&quot;], ''The Geelong Advertiser'', 14 March 2008, accessed 5 August 2008&lt;/ref&gt;

Selwood has been a life-long supporter of the Geelong Football Club,&lt;ref name=&quot;ggP18&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://bendigo.yourguide.com.au/news/sport/general/rookies-have-lots-to-do/543063.html &quot;Rookies have lots to do&quot;], ''The Bendigo Advertiser'', 28 December 2007, accessed 8 November 2007&lt;/ref&gt; and cites the club's own Hall of Fame member [[Gary Ablett, Sr.|Gary Ablett]] as a childhood idol, along with [[Sydney Swans|Sydney]] players [[Paul Kelly (footballer)|Paul Kelly]] and [[Brett Kirk]].&lt;ref name = kirk/&gt; He currently resides in Geelong West, where he lives with a pair of childhood friends.&lt;ref&gt;Sheahan, M, [http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/sport/afl/story/0,26576,25311801-19742,00.html &quot;Mike Sheahan talks with Joel Selwood for the first time&quot;] ''The Herald Sun'', 9 April 2009, accessed 10 April 2009&lt;/ref&gt; Prior to the 2009 AFL premiership season, Selwood was elected to the AFL Players Association committee as the Geelong alternate delegate representative.&lt;ref&gt;[http://aflpa.com.au/page/representatives &quot;Representatives – AFL Players Association&quot;], Australian Football League Players Association, 5 December 2008, accessed 5 December 2008&lt;/ref&gt;

Selwood is currently dating actress [[Esther Anderson (Australian actress)|Esther Anderson]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|last=Epstein|first=Jackie|title=Esther Anderson tells why she's sweet on Joel Selwood|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/esther-anderson-tells-why-shes-sweet-on-joel-selwood/story-e6frf96x-1226320720208|accessdate=7 April 2012|newspaper=[[Herald Sun]]|date=7 April 2012}}&lt;/ref&gt;

